comments.text:
<---Also a psychology student. It's too early to tell if she'd need 
therapy. At the moment she appears to be handling it fine, considering what 
she witnessed. But you're right, these kind of things can come back later. 
I was just pointing out that she wasn't in any danger at the moment. she's 
recounting her story without immediate fear, she's not in tears, not 
worried, she seems to feel relatively safe. It's one of those things where 
you would need to know her as a person or a patient before you could really 
know for certain. But none of us have the luxury. So we speculate, filling 
in the blanks with personal experience or knowledge. I wouldn't be too 
worried about her just off of the news report alone, but it'd be nice to 
check up on her in a couple of weeks.
comments.author: SilenceAngelic

comments.text:
+TheSchakalify +SilenceAngelic  Hi, educated psychology student here: 
You're talking bullshit.

The woman was the witness of a robbery and murder. She's still in partial 
shock. Many people would need proper therapy to get over something like 
that, as it can cause PTSD. There's nothing wrong with the way she speaks 
or acts, as it's perfectly normal behavior after what she's been through.
